Hi Friend!  as far as I can tell, this is about as common of a set of anxiety symptoms as there is.  And one I'm dealing with myself.  It's so easy for another person to tell you that you're going to be fine, and I could absolutely tell you that, but I recognize easier said than done.

That said, it's true :)

Sure thing!  It's hard to focus on the positive outcomes that your body has, but I've been getting physical therapy for a low back issue and i'm making progress, and it really helps to appreciate that I'm getting *stronger* not *weaker* despite this pile of anxiety (though it does make me miss bike rides and other workouts somewhat regularly).

But remember, if you came in worried about your heart, and your doctor told you that everything is fine UNLESS a few very specific thing start happening (and they aren't), then you should sleep well knowing you're plenty healthy.

Same!  I need to get a physical and circle up with the doctor, but I have random low-grade pain that I get anxious about that is randomly in my ribs, upper abs, or chest/pecs, all pretty close to the solar plexus.  Goes away when im with people or happy or in one way or another occupied.  Glad to hear that your doctor confirms what I expected:  this alone isn't enough to qualify as worth seeing as a real problem -- I am in good cardio shape and never feel low on energy when this stuff hits, luckily.
Way to go!  What kind of bike do you have?  I love bicycling too and riding keeps my brain right.

Hi friend! You'd be surprised how many physical symptoms are indeed merely anxiety related.  And I'm quite sure that whatever you think is cancer is overwhelmingly likely to be something else.  It's just your anxiety talking.

Best of luck, but if you haven't been to a doctor in awhile, getting them to tell you that you're fit as a fiddle will help get your mind right.
This is what I needed to hear right now, as a new sufferer of physical anxiety.  Thank you, friend!
